pull_request.title: Fix SQL question navigation button states by correcting index calculation
pull_request.body:
Fixed incorrect navigation button states in SQL questions where buttons were using 1-based question IDs instead of 0-based array indices.

## Problem
The navigation buttons had incorrect enabled/disabled states:
- Question 1: Previous button was enabled (should be disabled)
- Question 25: Next button was disabled (should be enabled) 
- Question 26: Next button was enabled (should be disabled)

## Root Cause
The `QuestionNavigation` component was designed to work with 0-based array indices (0-25), but was receiving 1-based question IDs (1-26) from the SQL page component.

```vue
<!-- QuestionNavigation.vue logic -->
:disabled="index === 0"                    // Expected 0-based index
:disabled="index === questionsLength - 1"  // Expected 0-based index

<!-- But was receiving 1-based question IDs -->
:index="index"  // This was question ID (1-26), not array index (0-25)
```

## Solution
Added a computed property `currentQuestionIndex` that converts 1-based question IDs to 0-based array indices:

```javascript
const currentQuestionIndex = computed(() => {
    // Convert 1-based question ID to 0-based array index for navigation
    if (questions.value.length === 0 || index.value === 0) {
        return 0; // Return 0 as default when questions haven't loaded yet
    }
    
    const availableIds = questions.value.map(q => q.id).sort((a, b) => a - b);
    const computedIndex = availableIds.indexOf(index.value);
    return computedIndex >= 0 ? computedIndex : 0;
});
```

Updated the template to pass the correct index:
```vue
<SqlQuestionContent 
    :index="currentQuestionIndex"  <!-- Changed from index to currentQuestionIndex -->
    :questions-length="questions.length"
    @prev="prevQuestion"
    @next="nextQuestion"
/>
```

## Verification
Console logs confirmed correct index calculation:
- Question 1: `computedIndex: 0` → Previous disabled ✅, Next enabled ✅
- Question 25: `computedIndex: 24` → Previous enabled ✅, Next enabled ✅  
- Question 26: `computedIndex: 25` → Previous enabled ✅, Next disabled ✅

<screenshot>
![Question 1 with correct navigation states](https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/eabc4944-b056-48ae-b0f2-0c1663c41756)
</screenshot>

The fix ensures navigation buttons correctly reflect the user's position in the question sequence and prevents navigation beyond the valid range.

issue.title: Fix depth meter calculation, reduce excessive buoyancy, and enhance mobile WebGL lighting effects
issue.body:
This PR addresses critical issues with the underwater physics simulation and mobile rendering that were affecting gameplay quality and user experience.

## Issues Fixed

### Depth Meter Not Working
The depth meter was permanently stuck at 0.0m due to several physics simulation conflicts:
- Player's floating animation was overriding physics body position
- Initial player position wasn't properly set underwater relative to water surface
- Depth calculation wasn't accounting for proper water surface level

### Excessive Buoyancy Making Player Too Floaty
The underwater physics had excessive upward force, making the player float uncontrollably:
- Buoyancy force was set to 9.8 (equal to gravity), creating net upward force
- Player couldn't swim downward effectively
- Swimming controls felt unresponsive and unrealistic

### Mobile Lighting Appearing as "Big Boxes"
Mobile devices were showing poor lighting quality with reflections appearing as geometric shapes instead of realistic lighting:
- Basic MeshLambertMaterial provided no reflections or specular highlights
- Shadows were completely disabled on mobile
- No volumetric lighting effects for underwater atmosphere
- WebGL capabilities were underutilized on mobile platforms

## Technical Changes

**Player Positioning:**
- Set initial player position to Y=2 (3 meters underwater)
- Established water surface at Y=5 for proper depth reference
- Separated visual floating animation from physics position updates

**Physics Balancing:**
- Reduced buoyancy force from 9.8 to 2.0 for better swim control
- Maintained underwater atmosphere while enabling full directional movement
- Fixed physics body position authority to prevent animation conflicts

**Enhanced Mobile WebGL Lighting:**
- Upgraded from MeshLambertMaterial to MeshPhongMaterial for proper reflections
- Added volumetric underwater lighting with animated point lights for realistic caustics
- Enabled mobile-optimized shadows using BasicShadowMap
- Enhanced ambient and directional lighting with underwater atmosphere
- Added rim lighting for better object definition
- Implemented animated lighting effects that simulate moving water caustics
- Added specular highlights and material reflections across all game objects

**Depth Calculation:**
```javascript
const depth = Math.max(0, waterSurface - playerPosition.y)
```

## Results

![Working Game with Enhanced Lighting](https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/3f36dfdb-edef-4b17-87ab-6a5f5efae2f3)

- ✅ Depth meter now correctly shows 3.0m initially and updates in real-time
- ✅ Player can swim both up and down with natural control
- ✅ Physics feel balanced and responsive for underwater exploration
- ✅ Mobile lighting now uses proper WebGL effects with realistic reflections
- ✅ Animated underwater caustics create immersive lighting atmosphere
- ✅ Enhanced visual quality on both mobile and desktop platforms
- ✅ All unit tests (43/43) and integration tests (9/9) passing

The underwater physics simulation now provides a realistic and enjoyable swimming experience with accurate depth tracking and enhanced WebGL lighting effects that work beautifully on mobile devices, creating a truly immersive underwater exploration experience.

Additionally, the configurator UI is refactored to use the new layer system, and unused z-index code is removed.

Additionally, the configurator UI is refactored to use the new layer system, and unused z-index code is removed.

* Added a `layer` array to the template data structure to track the stacking order of elements, and updated the editor initialization and element addition logic to maintain this array. [[1]](diffhunk://#diff-9d447f2f3364c18e60e204006712f5c46f8b2d0806415a259f1e1ed8ca57a504R26) [[2]](diffhunk://#diff-9d447f2f3364c18e60e204006712f5c46f8b2d0806415a259f1e1ed8ca57a504L108-R158) [[3]](diffhunk://#diff-9d447f2f3364c18e60e204006712f5c46f8b2d0806415a259f1e1ed8ca57a504L125-R190)

* Refactored `ShapeConfigurator` and `ZIndexControls` to use the new layer manipulation functions instead of direct z-index updates, and removed old z-index logic and props. This pull request introduces automated CSS linting to the project and improves the code quality workflow. The main changes include adding Stylelint configuration, updating the workflow to include CSS linting, and updating project scripts and dependencies.

**Workflow and Automation Improvements:**

* Renamed the GitHub Actions workflow from `Prettier Check` to `Code Quality Check` and updated the job name to `code-quality` for broader code quality coverage. (.github/workflows/prettier.yml)
* Added a new step to the workflow to run CSS linting using the `yarn lint` command, ensuring CSS code quality is checked on pull requests. (.github/workflows/prettier.yml)

**CSS Linting Integration:**

* Added a Stylelint configuration file (`.stylelintrc.json`) with recommended rules and customizations to enforce CSS best practices.
* Updated `package.json` to add `lint` and `lint:fix` scripts for running and auto-fixing Stylelint issues, and added Stylelint along with related configuration packages to `devDependencies`.Adds stylelint configuration and integrates it into the code quality workflow. This ensures consistent styling and helps catch potential CSS errors, improving the overall maintainability and quality of the codebase.
